Who Will Be The Next Soccer Star?¶

FIFA 2021 Data¶

CMSC320 Data Science Final Project¶

By: Erin Halper and Maggie Zhou¶

Introduction: This tutorial focuses on the FIFA 2021 video game data. The ultimate goal of the tutorial is to gain a better understanding of the information that differentiates higher ranked players versus lower ranked players. It will analyze the features in the data to better learn about and understand how those features affect a player’s rank. We want to see how this kind of data can be used to predict the skill of future players and consider how future players would rank based on the features available in this dataset. To do this, we will look for existing patterns and trends in the current 2021 data.

Specifically, this dataset contains all of male soccer players from the FIFA 2021 video game. The dataset has 17981 players (rows) and 9 columns. The columns included in the data are player_id, name, nationality, position, overall, age, hits, potential, and team. Let’s break down what each of these columns mean.

-player_id -> each player has their own unique numeric id
-name -> the full name of each player as -first last-
-nationality -> country the player is from and the national team they play for
-position -> position(s) the player plays, separated by by ‘|’ if they play multiple
-overall -> rank of the player in the videogame, ranging from 56 to 94 where better players are given higher numbered ranks
-age -> age of the player as of 2021, ranges from 17 to 43
-team -> club team that the player plays for as of 2021

The data set can be found here: https://www.kaggle.com/aayushmishra1512/fifa-2021-complete-player-data

These are the Python libraries we will be using to conduct the analysis.

#Quadratic Regression
np.polyfit(df3['age'], df3['freq'], 2)

def polyfit(x, y, degree):
    results = {}
    coeffs = np.polyfit(x, y, degree)
    p = np.poly1d(coeffs)
    #calculate r-squared
    yhat = p(x)
    ybar = np.sum(y)/len(y)
    ssreg = np.sum((yhat-ybar)**2)
    sstot = np.sum((y - ybar)**2)
    results['r_squared'] = ssreg / sstot
    print(results['r_squared'])
    print(coeffs)

polyfit(df3['age'], df3['freq'], 2)
polyfit(df3['age'], df3['freq'], 3)

#Average age vs. continent
conts = ['Asia', 'Africa', 'South America', 'North America', 'Australia/Oceania', 'Europe']
df2 = pandas.DataFrame(columns = ["continent", "avgAge"])

for c in conts:
    contPlayerAges = np.array([])
    for i in data.index:
        if data.at[i, "continent"] == c:
            contPlayerAges = np.append(contPlayerAges, [data.at[i, "age"] ])

    sum = np.sum(contPlayerAges)
    num = np.size(contPlayerAges)
    meanAge = sum/num


    #np.median(contPlayerAges)
    df2 = df2.append({"continent": c, "avgAge": meanAge}, ignore_index = True)

#Makes bar graph
ax = df2.plot.bar(x='continent', y='avgAge', rot=10)
plt.xlabel('Continent')
plt.ylabel('Average Player Age')
plt.title('Average Player Age from Each Continent')

#Calculate average age and rank for each country.
#The avgRank and numPlayers columns will be used later. 

countries
for j in countries.index:
    totalAge = 0
    totalRank = 0
    count = 0
    for i in data.index:
        if data.at[i, "nationality"] == countries.at[j, 'country']:
            totalAge += data.at[i, "age"]
            totalRank += data.at[i, "overall"]
            count += 1

    countries.at[j,'avgAge'] = totalAge/count
    countries.at[j,'avgRank'] = totalRank/count
    countries.at[j,'numPlayers'] = count

#Creates map to look at relationship between location and average age.
import folium


#marker color -> age group (ranges from 18-43)

m = folium.Map(location=[48, -5], zoom_start=2)
for i in countries.index:
    avgAge = countries.at[i, "avgAge"]

    if avgAge >= 18 and avgAge <= 25:
        folium.Marker(location=[countries.at[i, "lat"], countries.at[i, "long"]], popup = avgAge, 
        icon=folium.Icon(color="lightgreen")).add_to(m)

    elif avgAge >= 26 and avgAge <= 34:
        folium.Marker(location=[countries.at[i, "lat"], countries.at[i, "long"]], popup = avgAge, 
        icon=folium.Icon(color="green")).add_to(m)

    if avgAge >= 35 and avgAge <= 43:
        folium.Marker(location=[countries.at[i, "lat"], countries.at[i, "long"]], popup = avgAge, 
        icon=folium.Icon(color="darkgreen")).add_to(m)

Effect on Player's Rank¶

Now that we have a solid understanding of the general trends in the data, we are ready to explore how these features affect rank. We are going to look at how age, location, and position influence the rank of a player. For each, we will look at existing trends in the current data and hypothesis testing. For age, we will also explore some machine learning techniques of regression.

Rank and Age)¶

Let's take a look at the relationship between average age and rank.

Trend in Current Data)¶

Age and average player rank

In [255]:
import numpy as np

uniqueAges = set()
for i in data.index:
        if data.at[i, "age"] not in uniqueAges: 
            uniqueAges.add(data.at[i, "age"])

print(len(uniqueAges))



allAgePlayerRanks = {}
df2 = pandas.DataFrame(columns = ["age", "avgRank"])

for a in uniqueAges:
    AgePlayerRanks = np.array([])
    for i in data.index:
            if data.at[i, "age"] == a:
                AgePlayerRanks = np.append(AgePlayerRanks, [ data.at[i, "overall"] ])

    sum = np.sum(AgePlayerRanks)
    num = np.size(AgePlayerRanks)
    
    meanRanking = sum/num
    n = {a: meanRanking}
    allAgePlayerRanks.update(n)
    df2 = df2.append({"age": float(a), "avgRank": meanRanking}, ignore_index = True)


df2
df2.plot.scatter(x = 'age', y = 'avgRank')

#Quadratic Regression
def polyfit(x, y, degree):
    results = {}
    coeffs = np.polyfit(x, y, degree)
    p = np.poly1d(coeffs)
    #calculate r-squared
    yhat = p(x)
    ybar = np.sum(y)/len(y)
    ssreg = np.sum((yhat-ybar)**2)
    sstot = np.sum((y - ybar)**2)
    results['r_squared'] = ssreg / sstot
    print(results['r_squared'])
    print(coeffs)

polyfit(df2['age'], df2['avgRank'], 2)

#Average rank vs. continent
conts = ['Asia', 'Africa', 'South America', 'North America', 'Europe', 'Australia/Oceania']
df2 = pandas.DataFrame(columns = ["continent", "avgRank"])

for c in conts:
    contPlayerRanks = np.array([])
    for i in data.index:
        if data.at[i, "continent"] == c:
            contPlayerRanks = np.append(contPlayerRanks, [data.at[i, "overall"] ])

    sum = np.sum(contPlayerRanks)
    num = np.size(contPlayerRanks)
    meanRank = sum/num

    #np.median(contPlayerRanks)
    df2 = df2.append({"continent": c, "avgRank": meanRank}, ignore_index = True)

Next, let's take a look at where the top 100 ranked players are from!

If there are more than one player in the top 100 from the same country, then the map will show the higher ranked player for that country. The main marker color represents the player's ranking. The darker blue represents the highest ranked players (rank 90 to 94), and the ligher blue represents the lower ranked (out of the top 100, so still high!) players (rank 85 to 89).
The icon color represents the player's age. The lighter green represents the younger players (aged 18 to 26), and the darker green represents the mid-older players (aged 27 to 35).
Clicking on a marker will display information about the particular player being represented: name, age, rank.

In [258]:

Now, let's take a look at the average rank for each country. The map below shows the average rank for each country. There are four rank color classes for the map markers. The average rankings range from 58 to 78.
The pink markers denote the countries with an average ranking between 58 and 62.
The orange markers denote the countries with an average ranking between 63 and 67.
The red markers denote the countries with an average ranking between 68 and 72.
The black markers denote the countries with an average ranking between 73 and 78.
